pr_body:
Merge flappy with flappy-birds

- Add up-arrow key functionality for bird movement
- Refine bird rotation for smoother gameplay
- Implement a moving background for enhanced visuals
- Incorporate flapping wings animation
- Adjust the starting point of bottom pipes for better visuals
- Enhance collision detection, using masks, for increased precision
- Introduce a sound effect upon collision, with the bird falling to the ground
- Tweak the points sound effect timing for improved feedback
- Update the game font and add an outline, to resemble the original Flappy Bird
- Replace the existing Sugargame file with the latest version
- Add flake8 file

@chimosky @sourabhaa

`pygame.K_RIGHT` will always be true because pygame.K_RIGHT  is a non-zero integer.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 18, 17, 41, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Dimi20cen', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1329081345, 'comment_body': 'Fixed', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 18, 17, 42, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Dimi20cen', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1330515870, 'comment_body': 'The comparison is for equality hence `==` and not for identity which is done with `is` as it compares if both objects are the same while the equality compares two values.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 19, 18, 1, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1331085351, 'comment_body': "Your point about `==` checking for equality and `is` checking for identity is accurate, but the issue in the original statement `if event.key == pygame.K_LEFT or pygame.K_RIGHT:` is with the use of the `or` operator. The way it's written, Python evaluates it as `(event.key == pygame.K_LEFT)` or `(pygame.K_RIGHT)`. Since `pygame.K_RIGHT` is a non-zero integer constant, it evaluates as `True` in a boolean context, making the entire or condition always `True`. Therefore, this condition doesn't accurately check `if event.key` is either `pygame.K_LEFT or pygame.K_RIGHT`. 

When this code is used, the game starts only when the left or the right arrow keys are pressed
```
if event.key == pygame.K_LEFT or event.key == pygame.K_RIGHT:
```

When this code is used, the game starts when any key is pressed
```
if event.key == pygame.K_LEFT or pygame.K_RIGHT:
```
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 20, 6, 50, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Dimi20cen', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1331590839, 'comment_body': "I agree.  But easier to demonstrate;

```
>>> import pygame
>>> x = pygame.K_DOWN
>>> x == pygame.K_LEFT or x == pygame.K_RIGHT
False
>>> x == pygame.K_LEFT or pygame.K_RIGHT
1073741903
>>> if 1073741903:
...     print('true')
... 
true
>>> 
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 20, 12, 56, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'quozl', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1331659880, 'comment_body': 'I understand better now.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 9, 20, 13, 44, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'chimosky', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Port to python3 and add functionality
pr_body:
- Fixed issue with adjusting pygame window to screensize
- Added mouseclicking for changing lanes
- Added pause functionality, either with clicking on pause button or by pressing space
- Added homebutton, during scorescreen

@chimosky @sourabhaa

pr_title: Port to python3 and add functionality
pr_body:
- Fixed issue with adjusting pygame window to screensize
- Added mouseclicking for changing lanes
- Added pause functionality, either with clicking on pause button or by pressing space
- Added homebutton, during scorescreen

@chimosky @sourabhaa

pr_body:
Issue:
When horizontally scrolling, a part of the popup help messages would be created in the non-visible part of the screen.

Solution:
Change the x value in `self.activity.sw.get_vadjustment().get_value()`, to be the horizontal adjustment of the screen.

Fixes #75

@chimosky @sourabhaa, kindly review

pr_title: Prevent Gtk-CRITICAL warning when removing toolbar item
pr_body:
Issue: When windows size gets decreased to a specific point and then increase again the following warning occurs, `Gtk-CRITICAL **: 13:29:23.501: gtk_toolbar_remove: assertion 'content_to_remove != NULL' failed`

Change: Added a safety check to ensure that `self._coordinates_toolitem` is in  `self._view_toolbar` before attempting to remove it.

pr_title: Change homepage and middleclick function on links
pr_body: Regarding the homepage's search box, I saw the discussion that keeping the search-box round is important. However index.html is not very readable, at least for me ( i dont really do html/css/js ) so I can't find the reason that makes the search-box so "stubborn". If you think it's a good idea, I'm open to rewrite the code for the index file from the ground up, that might be more fun.

pr_title: Prevent Gtk-CRITICAL warning when removing _stop and _separator from toolbar
pr_body:
Issue:
When the window gets resized the following warning occurs, Gtk-CRITICAL **: 03:45:45.314: gtk_toolbar_remove: assertion 'content_to_remove != NULL' failed

Change:
Added a safety check to ensure that a toolbar item has toolbar as a parent before attempting to remove it. This resolves a Gtk-CRITICAL warning that occurred when trying to remove an item that was not in the toolbar.

Fixes #32
@chimosky @sourabhaa

pr_title: Add multi line text input and drawing input
pr_body:
Relevant to issue #17 

The code is not working properly and there are still issues with transmiting the drawing and text to the shared activity instance.

As you can see in the commits, I used a custom gtk.TextView to replace the gtk Entry for the input field. One problem I faced was that, if I understand correctly, the sugar's gtk-widgets.css doesn't style textview in a similar way as entry. Would you suggest I manage the css for textview in the source code of chat's activity? 

Also, currently when a user sends messages consecutively, they all bundle up in the same box. I was thinking that giving each separate message its own box, would look better. What do you think?

@chimosky @sourabhaa
